<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="34" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="34">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="7" pageNumber="34">
This genus originally described from Iran with only one species, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Ficothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ficothrips moundi" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="moundi">Ficothrips moundi</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation pageId="7" pageNumber="34">Minaei 2012b</bibRefCitation>
). This monobasic genus is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Scolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Scolothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Scolothrips</taxonomicName>
or 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Parascolothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Parascolothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Parascolothrips</taxonomicName>
. Morphologically, 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Ficothrips" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Ficothrips" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Ficothrips</taxonomicName>
is interesting because simultaneously bears two charchter states that have been evolved rarely in 
<taxonomicName family="Thripidae" lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" rank="family">Thripidae</taxonomicName>
: nine antennal segments and severall long setae on the pronotum. The species was collected on fig leaves infested by 
<taxonomicName class="Arachnida" family="Tetranychidae" genus="Eotetranychus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Eotetranychus hirsti" order="Trombidiformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsti">Eotetranychus hirsti</taxonomicName>
Pritchard and Baker (
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Pilidiophora" family="Lineidae" genus="Acari" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Acari" order="Heteronemertea" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" phylum="Nemertea" rank="genus">Acari</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName family="Tetranychidae" lsidName="" pageId="7" pageNumber="34" rank="family">Tetranychidae</taxonomicName>
) and the low density of species suggest that it may be a predator on that mite (
<bibRefCitation pageId="7" pageNumber="34">Minaei 2012b</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
